##Interview with author Fang Fang: It's necessary to maintain your sense of honesty and justice

Wechat, chinanewsweekly

Function introduction, here is "China News weekly" the head of the weekly gentleman, the influence has the influence you. Come with me to break through the fog, to find the truth, to watch the Times.

"I am not a man of public affairs at all. But I am a man of the people and the world. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Fang Fang, China News Service

Interview with author Fang Fang

To maintain their integrity and sense of justice

By Wei Yanzhang

PUBLISHED: February 17,2020

Since the outbreak, Fang Fang, a well known writer based in Wuhan, has been writing online about everything she's seen and thought about, trying to talk nonstop. "Isn't it what we writers are supposed to do, " she said, "to keep a record of people and Events In these extraordinary times? "

On Feb. 10, Fang Fang wrote an exclusive interview with China News weekly about her life before and after the city's closure, her grief and anger after her death, and her role in public affairs as an intellectual.

"I could have escaped during the siege, but it never occurred to me. "

China News Week: You first learned that Wuhan has "suspected SARS pneumonia" that moment, what are you doing? What was your reaction when you heard the news?

Fang Fang: I learned this from my brother on December 31 last year. There was a small group of us, me and my three brothers. At that time, everyone immediately warned each other, do not go out, do not go to crowded places, do not go to the hospital, go out to wear a mask. After the SARS outbreak in 2003, everyone had this basic vigilance.

China Newsweek: Do you know exactly what it was like at that moment when the pneumonia was really bad? What was your reaction to the news? What did you do?

Fang Fang: I should have been on high alert on January 18. There's been a lot of chatter on the Internet. After all, it's an epidemic. From that day on, I went out wearing a mask. But my house is a one-man operation, I drive my own car, I don't meet many people. I'm just so angry inside. Because up until now, we've been told that it's not going to be passed from one person to another, and despite all our precautions, everyone trusts the government. Even my brother said it was too big for the government to hide. I've said the same thing to some of my friends.

China News Week: When you learned of the siege of Wuhan, did you ever consider leaving Wuhan temporarily? What did you imagine your life would be like if you stayed in Wuhan?

Fang Fang: I went to the airport on the night of January 22 to pick up my daughter, who was returning from a trip to Japan. By that time Wuhan was already quite nervous and panicky. When Mr Zhong Nanshan's "human-to-human" message became public, the government did not speak, and ordinary people panicked, with few pedestrians on the streets. This panic, it's inexplicable, but it's real, and it's spreading fast. Before I went to the airport, I said to my friend, "the wind is blowing and the water is cold. ".

Meanwhile, on the same day, my daughter's father was hospitalized in Shanghai, saying he might have been hit. My daughter had dinner with her father before she went to Japan, so I was more worried that my daughter would get infected. It was late at night when my flight was delayed and I picked up my daughter. Neither of US took off our masks in the car, so we decided to put her in isolation for a week, and I brought her some food. After I dropped her off, I stopped for gas on the way back to my house, and when I got home, it was around 1:00 a.m.

At this time opened the computer, the first time that the city will be closed. It was possible to pack my bags and get out, but I didn't really think about it. Of all the people in Wuhan, all of them shut up in their homes, my condition is almost one of the best compared to that of ordinary people. If people can live, I can live. So, not much to worry about. All the same, trust the government. At this point, the government will have a way to contain the outbreak.

China Newsweek: This year's New Year is too special for every Chinese. How do you usually spend New Year's without epidemics?

Fang Fang: I used to do the same thing. I used to stay home. The only difference is that one day in the middle of the New Year, I would visit my great uncle Yang Shuzi for New Year's and dinner, to meet a group of relatives. Then the daughter stays at home for a few days. For the rest, stay home and read, Watch TV, and write. I usually stay at home and don't go out for ten days, so I don't find it difficult to stay at home because of my career.

"Li Wenliang's death makes me very sad and angry. "

China News Week: I see that your "story of closing off the city" involves a lot of news and news related to Wuhan. How does your mood change these days as you read these messages?

Fang Fang: In the early stages, Wuhan was chaotic and panicky, but we couldn't convey that kind of panic. I'M GONNA help the government. That's the basic idea. It can be a complicated time, when you know what's going on, or even what's causing the delay, but you have to give up something. There's no way around it. This is a big deal, and we need to work together with the government to fight it. But in fact, by the first day of the seventh lunar month, the whole country pays attention to Wuhan, Wuhan People's mood has begun to stabilize, has begun to accept can not go out the day, and has become accessible. This is a turning point. But later, as more and more people fell ill, and the hospital simply can not accept so many people, over time, things happen in everyone around, it is impossible not to feel depressed and uneasy. Li Wenliang's death, the reason caused a tremendous wave, in fact, is also suppressed for a long time people need an outlet, vent their feelings.

China Newsweek: When you are in a bad mood, what do you do to digest those feelings?

Fang Fang: I've always been a very rational person. I've had three surgeries in five years, and my colleagues joke that I've come to the hospital alive, that I'm sane enough to remove the lesions at the best of times. There aren't many people who can do that. Every surgery, it's like a computer reboot. I think I did the right thing. And the other day, even I had a moment of tension and panic. I'm not nervous about myself. Even though I had been to the hospital three times between New Year's Day and the 18th. I've been using a process of elimination to rule out the possibility that I might be infected. I've come to the conclusion that I can't be infected. My stress comes from the uncertainty of my family. I keep telling myself to be calm, to be rational, how bad the worst is. The worst that could happen is that my daughter could get infected. But she's young. She'll be fine. I asked my daughter to keep an eye on her body, but she was fine, and her father ruled out new pneumonia. After that, we all made it through the 14-day quarantine.

China Newsweek: What is the situation of your family these days?

Fang Fang: I grew up in Wuhan, and I have two older brothers. My brother happens to live near the south China seafood market, so he's the one to worry about the most. But the good news is he left early to wear a mask. Today I saw that the number of patients in their community ranks first in Wuhan. His place is our biggest concern. My brother is at USTC, which is far away from Hankou, and he doesn't have many contacts, so he'll be fine, I know that. The good news is everyone's safe for now. The city and the gates have been sealed for nearly 20 days, and anyone affected by the outbreak has probably had it by now. It should be said that we all passed the most dangerous time smoothly.

China News Week: What were you doing when you saw the news of Li Wenliang's death? Next, what did you do with this message?

Fang Fang: I had just finished writing that day's blog. Hearing the news of Li Wenliang's death, I felt very sad and indignant. This mood, may be outside the Wuhan people can not understand.

China Newsweek: You also wrote the article "remember all this" during the 1998 flood. In your opinion, is it the writer's responsibility to record the great disaster when it happens?

Fang Fang: When the flood came, I could run to the Levee for a day, and I was young. Now I'm almost an old man, and even when I want to volunteer, I'm afraid of getting in trouble. So, I've been telling myself that I'm helping by staying home and making sure I'm not sick. So, when I'm not sick, isn't it what we writers are supposed to do, to document people and Events of this kind in times of crisis? In fact, a lot of reporters, each person has their own point of view, so much better. This will allow future generations to truly know the truth about what will happen in 2020.

China Newsweek: At what age did you begin to think of yourself as an "intellectual" ? At that age, what did you make of your role as an "intellectual" ?

Fang Fang: I grew up among intellectuals. In those days, highly educated people were intellectuals. My grandfather graduated from Beijing University and became a teacher; my father graduated from Shanghai Jiaotong University and became an engineer. They all naturally consider themselves intellectuals. After I graduated from college, it was natural for me to think of myself as an intellectual. Back then, it was that simple.

China Newsweek: Your father and grandfather were intellectuals. I read in the public record that you had a period where you spent a lot of time looking at their lives, and you wrote about their lives. How do you remember your grandfather and your father when you weren't looking specifically at family history?

Fang Fang: My grandfather died young, and I didn't know anything about him. When he began to write, he saw some information, and his students'memoirs, and then he came to know something about him. I knew my father well, of course, but I was too young to understand his feelings. They are all just a scholar, have no interest in politics, also have no intention of official career. They're just trying to do their job. It's like my whole family. I'm the same way myself. I'm the president of the provincial cooperative, which is what they want me to be. My brother also advised me not to be, to write a good novel on it. I was too embarrassed to refuse at that time, as the president of the Association was not an official anyway, so I agreed. We're all people who don't like too much contact with the outside world.

China Newsweek: around the late 1980s, you started to write about the intellectual lives and circumstances of your grandfather and father. What new insights have you gained from retracing their past?

Fang Fang: Like I said, they're just college kids. Care about the world care about people's livelihood, not concerned about politics, also do not intend to participate. I knew too little about my grandfather, who had just graduated from college when he died. But my father kept a bunch of journals. He kept a diary from 1942 until his death. Like many intellectuals in China, he is patriotic, has a sense of justice, wants a quiet and peaceful life, loves his family, frets about political movements and is pessimistic that he has nowhere to turn. Nevertheless, he is still studying hard, hoping to be useful one day. During the Cultural Revolution, my father was at home, reading and reading. They're two sad generations. My grandfather was killed by the Japanese because of the war and social unrest, while my father was more restless in the political movement.

China Newsweek: How did the process of writing and understanding your grandfather and father affect you? Will your expectations of yourself as an "intellectual" change as you understand the life of your grandfather and father?

Fang Fang: My profession is not like theirs. They could have done it more purely academically, even if they hadn't had the chance. But my brother and brother, they can. But my career requires me to pay more attention to a wider range of social life requires me to have a deeper understanding. Each person's growth process and the life background are deciding each other is different. You don't need to know your grandfather or your father. As you grow up, as you get older, as you become more knowledgeable, as you change your mind, things will change. You don't have to rub it in your father's face.

China Newsweek: Until 2015, the public's impression of you seems to be more of a writer buried in writing than an intellectual engaged in public affairs. Is this impression a misunderstanding of you?

Fang Fang: I'm not much of a public affairs Guy Right now. A lot of things, it's not what happened to me, it's what happened to me. In recent years, some things, only I do my job responsibility; some things, is the criticism of my novel, I do not accept it, retort. Into an incident. I'm still not an active voice in public affairs.

For example, this time, I just wanted to record a few things, did not expect this. To be honest, I'm surprised. I didn't even think about writing it every day, like, eighth grade. I am a laid-back person. All things, so to speak, none of which I had anticipated, had provoked me into disobedience. I'm still a person who likes to stay home and write and read. Occasionally idle, hang out with friends, eat and drink. People always say, "let's enjoy the peace and quiet. ". But it is necessary to maintain one's own honesty and sense of justice and integrity.

China Newsweek: It seems to the outside world that as you pay more and more attention to public affairs, your choice of literary materials will change. Does it seem to you that the relationship between attention to public affairs and Literary Creation Affects Each Other? Or are they separate and independent of each other?

Fang Fang: As I said, I'm not a public affairs person at all. But I will pay attention to people's livelihood and the world, and I will pay attention to my personal life. So sometimes, I retweet things from other people that I agree with. I don't have much of a voice myself. I'm ashamed. So, that's not a valid question.

China News Week: After the outbreak, you issued a warning to your colleagues, "pay attention to the bottom line in eulogizing after the disaster. ". When you were chairman of the Hubei Provincial Cooperative Association, did you have any similar problems? If so, what were the circumstances? How did you handle it?

Fang Fang: There are people like that all the time, and some of the writing, it's really hard to read, like the one that says, "thanks for the crown. " It's disgusting. When I was president of the Association, I divided writers into those who were good at writing the main theme, those who had a good background in writing, and those who were already famous for their own style. Give help or delegate tasks according to these three categories. Of course, there are no obvious boundaries. The writers guild. When something big happens, there's always a mission. After the Wenchuan County earthquake, I took my own team to the city of Hanyuan, which was built with the aid of Hubei. I served as the President of the Association for eleven years, and did not encounter any difficulties. Even if there were, I could take care of it myself. In fact, the co-workers of the Association and I have a good relationship, some of whom I watched them grow up. After all, I've been with the writers guild for 30 years.

China Newsweek: What did you do to make yourself proud when you were chairman of the Hubei Provincial Writers'association? Now look back at the time as the chairman of the Hubei Provincial Cooperation Association this experience, what are the regrets?

Fang Fang: I don't feel like I have anything to be proud of, but there's plenty to be proud of at work. My greatest regret is that I could not help the poet Yu Xiuhua. I always hoped that she would be transferred to the CO-OP, so that her life would be more stable. Despite my best efforts,. However, in the coordination, it seems that I am the chairman, in fact, I am also a man of few words.

Duty Editor: Luo Xiaolan
